    "title": "🤰 PREECLAMPSIA VS GESTATIONAL HTN",
    "content": "Hypertension after 20 weeks is a major Canadian exam topic.<br><br><table><tr><th>Feature</th><th>Gestational HTN</th><th>Preeclampsia</th></tr><tr><td>BP</td><td>> 140/90</td><td>> 140/90</td></tr><tr><td>Proteinuria</td><td>None</td><td><b>Positive</b> (or organ failure)</td></tr><tr><td>Edema</td><td>Common</td><td>Significant</td></tr></table><br><div style='background:#fef2f2; border-left:5px solid var(--red); padding:10px; border-radius:8px;'><b>⚠️ Exam Trap:</b> In Canada, the definition of Preeclampsia no longer <i>strictly</i> requires proteinuria if there is <b>End-organ dysfunction</b> (low platelets, high Cr, or visual symptoms). If BP is > 160/110, it is <b>Severe</b>!</div>",
    "quiz": { "q": "What is the only definitive treatment for severe preeclampsia?", "a": "Delivery of the fetus and placenta." }
